{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496432"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:46:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:46:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1361"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1361"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.08,0.07,0.12,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46970"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1361","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1361"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1361"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31732"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"355"},{"type":"tags","id":"1258"},{"type":"tags","id":"2418"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11145"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17911"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39220"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46970"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a two-month history of early satiety. She is no longer able to eat her normal sized meals and says her symptoms have been getting worse over the last week. She has no other symptoms. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. The physical examination is unremarkable and a contrast study (barium meal) is arranged (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Gastric perforation","Gastro-colic fistula","Oesophageal diverticulum","Para-oesophageal hernia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis contrast study shows a substantial proportion of the stomach is above the diaphragm. Whilst difficult to see, the cardio-oesophageal junction appears to be below the diaphragm. Of the gastric component within the chest, the greater curve is uppermost. This \u003Cstrong\u003Epara-oesophageal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E has undergone organo-axial rotation. Many para-oesophageal hernias never cause any symptoms. When they do, the problems are usually those related to partial obstruction leading to early satiety.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E gastrointestinal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E would show up as a filling defect in the stomach - and many of these are incidental findings. There is no evidence of any contrast outside the lumen of the stomach. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn most cases of \u003Cstrong\u003Egastric perforation\u003C/strong\u003E, there is sudden onset of severe abdominal pain. However, sometimes small perforations can seal off rapidly, with little evidence of peritoneal soiling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA\u003Cstrong\u003E gastro-colic fistula \u003C/strong\u003Ewould show contrast entering the colon - usually the transverse colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERugal folds can see seen going across the lumen of this structure, implying that it is stomach and very unlikely to be an \u003Cstrong\u003Eoesophageal diverticulum.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most para-oesophageal hernias are incidental findings."],"references":["Roman S, Kahrilas PJ. The diagnosis and management of hiatus hernia. BMJ 2014;349:g6154. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/349/bmj.g6154"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31732"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1361"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15146"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15146"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d31e7c81-455b-4fa8-ad8a-1d99aa04eb1a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/d31e7c81-455b-4fa8-ad8a-1d99aa04eb1a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":539,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"31732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/31732"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-06-14T13:24:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T15:54:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1361"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46970"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","n